## A grid that balances orientations

I switched to a CSS Grid where each photo occupies multiple cells depending on orientation:

- Landscape → 2 rows × 3 columns
- Square → 2 × 2
- Portrait → 3 × 2

This normalizes occupied area so landscape and portrait frames feel comparable, while squares read smaller (which matches how we usually obtain them — via cropping).

### The classes

```css
/* Grid container */
main > ul {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(5rem, 1fr));
  gap: 1.5rem;
}

/* Spans per orientation */
main > ul .grid-landscape { grid-row: span 2; grid-column: span 3; }
main > ul .grid-square    { grid-row: span 2; grid-column: span 2; }
main > ul .grid-portrait  { grid-row: span 3; grid-column: span 2; }
```

### Caption placement logic

- Landscape and square: caption at the bottom edge.
- Portrait: caption on the side, rotated, to preserve vertical space.

```css
/* Bottom caption */
.caption-bottom figure { padding-bottom: 2rem; }
.caption-bottom figcaption { bottom: 0.5rem; left: 0.6rem; right: 0.6rem; }

/* Side caption for portraits */
.caption-side figure { padding-left: 2rem; }
.caption-side figcaption { top: 0.6rem; left: 0.5rem; bottom: 0.6rem; writing-mode: vertical-rl; }
```

