## Polaroid borders as a perceptual tool

I frame each image with two borders:

- A thin inner line in a light gray to separate the photo from the outer border.
- A thick off‑white outer border — not pure white, but bright enough to act as a perceptual white reference.

Why it matters:

- The off‑white border gives the eye a stable “paper white,” helping the viewer adapt to ambient light or screen calibration.
- Against a darker page background, the border boosts the perceived dynamic range of the photo without editing the image itself.
- Borders are CSS, not baked into files (better compression; no ringing on sharp edges).

```css
/* Inner and outer borders on the single‑photo page */
main > figure img {
  padding: 0.1rem;                 /* thin inner separator */
  background-color: oklch(92% 0 0deg);
  border: 5vh 5vw solid oklch(95% 0 0deg);  /* thick outer border */
  box-shadow: var(--elevation-3);
}
```

